<subSubSection id="4F90654006090911FF61F8E7FD4DF851" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="073536CB06090911FF61F8E7FD4DF851" blockId="28.[151,1437,1804,1973]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD906090911FF61F8E7FEFBF8E5" bold="true" box="[199,295,1804,1829]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Biology.</emphasis>
As is typical for 
<collectingRegion id="C54EF82906090911FE51F8E7FD80F8E5" box="[503,604,1804,1829]" country="Sri Lanka" name="Southern" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Southern</collectingRegion>
Ocean orbiniids, little is known concerning the biology of 
<taxonomicName id="C08A4D4806090911FAB7F8E6FA49F8E4" box="[1297,1429,1805,1828]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Leitoscoloplos" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="mawsoni">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD906090911FAB7F8E6FA49F8E4" box="[1297,1429,1805,1828]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">L. mawsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, collections from the Australian Antarctic program from 
<date id="7334100B06090911FC29F8DBFB9FF889" box="[911,1091,1840,1865]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="2005-12">December 2005</date>
had two obvious size classes: (1) large mature adults with ripe gametes and (2) small juveniles. Many specimens from 
<date id="7334100B06090911FB36F8BEFAD9F8AD" box="[1168,1285,1876,1901]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" value="2005-12">Dec. 2005</date>
were packed with eggs with average diameters of 215 µm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
